Train a classifier which predicts time to merge of a PR

In this notebook, we train a classifier which predicts the time to merge of a Pull Request by classifying time_to_merge into one of the 10 discrete bins defined in github_PR_EDA.ipynb using some engineered features.

Define Training and Evaluation Pipeline

In this section, we will initialize various vanilla classifiers which can help classify time to merge into one of the 10 bins defined. In github_PR_EDA.ipynb, we split the time-to-merge values into 10 equally populated bins which are as follows:

Class 0 : < 3 hrs
Class 1 : < 6 hrs
Class 2 : < 15 hrs
Class 3 : < 24 hrs / 1 day
Class 4 : < 36 hrs / 1.5 days
Class 5 : < 60 hrs / 2.5 days
Class 6 : < 112 hrs / ~4.5 days
Class 7 : < 190 hrs / ~8 days
Class 8 : < 462 hrs / ~19 days
Class 9: > 462 hrs

[44]
def train_evaluate_classifier(clf, xtrain, ytrain, xtest, ytest):
    # Train our classifier
    clf.fit(xtrain, ytrain)

    # Make predictions
    preds = clf.predict(xtest)

    # View classification report
    print(classification_report(ytest, preds))

    # Plot confusion matrix heatmap
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 12))
    cf_matrix = confusion_matrix(ytest, preds)
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n".format(value) for value in cf_matrix.flatten()]
    group_percentages = [
        "{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf_matrix.flatten() / np.sum(cf_matrix)
    ]
    box_labels = [
        f"{v1}{v2}".strip() for v1, v2 in zip(group_counts, group_percentages)
    ]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf_matrix.shape[0], cf_matrix.shape[1])

    sns.heatmap(cf_matrix, cmap="OrRd", annot=box_labels, fmt="")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted TTM Label")
    plt.ylabel("True TTM Label")
    plt.title("Confusion Matrix Heatmap")

Train using pruned features

In the previous notebook we performed some feature engineering and pruned the features down to 96. However, it might be possible that pruning the features down based on the models' evaluation score would yield a more generalizable and accurate model. So in this section, we get subsets of the features from the training and test dataset based on important feature ranks calculated using Recursive Feature Elimination. RFE lets us select features recursively by assigning weights to the features and ranking the features.

From the confusion matrices above, it seems that the Naive bayes and SVM models are heavily biased towards a few classes. The random forest and XG Boost models seem to be less biased and have mis-classifications within the bordering classes amongst the ordinal classes.

Overall, the models (naive bayes, random forest and xgboost )seem to perform slightly better when trained on the top selected subset of the features.

Compared to all the models, XGboost seems to perform better than the rest on the subset of the important features.

Conclusion

In this notebook, we explored various vanilla classifiers such as Naive Bayes, SVM, Random Forests, etc. The XG Boost Classifier is able to predict the classes with a 22% accuracy when trained on an important subset of the features. However, none of the methods seem to perform sufficiently well.

Since the label/output variable of the github PR dataset is an ordinal variable, an ordinal classifier might yield a higher performance.

As next steps, we will try ordinal classification models and look into more feature selection techniques.
